The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 LOOSE CHANGE

 ING Vysya Mutual Fund has unveiled its mid-cap fund, an open-ended scheme that will primarily invest in mid-cap stocks within the market capitalisation range of Rs 100 crore to Rs 2,000 crore. The minimum investment amount is Rs 2,000 and the scheme will provide dividend, growth and bonus options. There is no entry or exit load during the IPO, but an exit load not exceeding 1 per cent (for investments below Rs 1 crore) will be charged for redemption within 180 days from the investment date. The IPO is open till May 9.

 HSBC Mutual Fund has launched its third equity fund?HSBC Midcap Equity Fund ?which will primarily invest in mid-cap stocks but also have the freedom to move a part of assets towards fixed income securities if the fund manager becomes cautious or negative on the equity markets. The minimum investment is Rs 5,000 and it will stop accepting applications once its assets cross Rs 700 crore. It will charge an entry load of 2.25 per cent on all investments below Rs 5 crore and none above that, including during the initial offer period, which is open till May 3. 

 SUUTI has declared a 6 per cent dividend for two monthly income plans ?MIP 2000 (III) and MIP 2001 ? for 2005-06.




